Rating: 3
Took clnordberg's advice and made 1.5 shortbread (half batch with cinnamon, remaining without). Other modifications ensued: used whole wheat/kamut flour blend and kamut bread, sugar mixture included lemon zest from one full lemon, nutmeg and cloves. Subbed 2 tbsp of the cinnamon-free batch instead of flour. Total butte usage: 1 cup (practically half for the topping). Topping was a mix of the cinnamon batch of shortbread, 2 tbsp crushed toasted walnuts and, well, bread. Oh yes...and pears drizzled in lemon juice :) We had a hard pear variety (brown skin) that worked well. Very kid-friendly and this works in muffin cups if you half the time. Looks pretty when you pop them out (we have those silicon-type muffin trays). Layers! For that fact alone, I'd try this in summer with peaches and a vanilla-infused shortbread.

Rating: 3
Delish! I changed this recipe quite a bit. I made 1.5 times the shortbread base and used 2/3 for the base and 1/3 as the topping (did not use any bread). Also, cut the drizzled butter down to 1/4 cup (since there was butter in the topping) and used 2.5 lbs yellow cooking apples. I also sliced the apples in my food processor. Great reviews, even after overnight in my fridge. A nice fall alternative to pumpkin bars.

Rating: 4
Better the next day! I used the apples that I had on hand, which were a mix. I also took the advise of others and cut the butter to one stick for the shortbread and one for apples. I used 1 cup of all purpose and 1 cup whole wheat flour, next time I will do 1/2 C whole wheat and 1 1/2 all purpose flours. Added cinnamon to the shortbread batter and ground clove to the apples. The topping was a mix of brown sugar, all purpose flour and oats processed in the food processor and then dotted with butter before baking.Next time I'll add some chopped or slivered almonds. Not very sweet so you may want to compliment with some sweetened whipped cream or ice cream. Outstanding!

